er of 2021.&nbsp; The real-time communication capability added to the experiment under this award has enabled us to calibrate the systems&nbsp;more efficiently (since we can change settings&nbsp;on the stations and get&nbsp;real-time feedback by looking at the data collected), analyze the data one year&nbsp;sooner&nbsp;(since we won?t have to wait until the end of the season to pick up the&nbsp;data physically), and respond to multi-messenger alerts from other experiments&nbsp;(which we cannot do without real-time high bandwidth&nbsp;communications).</div><br>\n<p>\n\t\t\t\t      \tLast Modified: 05/06/2022<br>\n\t\t\t\t\tModified by: Abigail&nbsp;G&nbsp;Vieregg</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"porSideCol\"></div>\n</div>",
  "por_txt_cntn": "\nUnder this 1-year award, we added real-time communication capability to the Radio Neutrino Observatory in Greenland (RNO-G) experiment in its first year of deployment, by adding an internal LTE network, which enabled real-time communication with each station through its first season of operations.  RNO-G is a new ground-based array of radio detectors that is being constructed at Summit Station in Greenland that aims to make the first detection of the highest energy astrophysical neutrinos. RNO-G opens a new window to the universe through ultra-high energy neutrino astrophysics, extending the energy range of neutrino telescopes and probing the nature of the highest energy accelerators in the universe.  RNO-G is comprised of 35 stations of radio antennas and associated electronics, spaced on a 1.25 km grid.  RNO-G monitors the ice below to look for impulsive radio signals generated when ultra-high energy neutrinos interact in the Greenlandic ice sheet.  Each RNO-G station is based on an efficient, hybrid design that includes deep antennas that provide the main trigger and reconstruction information, and surface antennas that provide additional reconstruction information, a cosmic ray veto, and background rejection.  \n\nThe work performed under this award was to procure, test, characterize, and install the LTE network at Summit Station.  Team members traveled to Summit Station to do this work in the summer of 2021.  The real-time communication capability added to the experiment under this award has enabled us to calibrate the systems more efficiently (since we can change settings on the stations and get real-time feedback by looking at the data collected), analyze the data one year sooner (since we won?t have to wait until the end of the season to pick up the data physically), and respond to multi-messenger alerts from other experiments (which we cannot do without real-time high bandwidth communications).\n\n\t\t\t\t\tLast Modified: 05/06/2022\n\n\t\t\t\t\tSubmitted by: Abigail G Vieregg"
